# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: approximation-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In computer science and operations research, **approximation algorithms** are efficient algorithms that find approximate solutions to optimization problems (in particular NP-hard problems) with provable guarantees on the distance of the returned solution to the optimal one.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Approximation algorithms naturally arise in the field of theoretical computer science as a consequence of the widely believed P ≠ NP conjecture.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Under this conjecture, a wide class of optimization problems cannot be solved exactly in polynomial time.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] The field of approximation algorithms, therefore, tries to understand how closely it is possible to approximate optimal solutions to such problems in polynomial time.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In an overwhelming majority of the cases, the guarantee of such algorithms is a multiplicative one expressed as an approximation ratio or approximation factor i.e., the optimal solution is always guaranteed to be within a (predetermined) multiplicative factor of the returned solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] However, there are also many approximation algorithms that provide an additive guarantee on the quality of the returned solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] An example of an approximation algorithm with a multiplicative guarantee is the Christofides-Serdyukov algorithm for the Travelling salesman problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] It provides a travelling salesman tour in a metric of length at most 3/2 times that of a shortest such tour.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] A classic example of approximation algorithm providing an additive guarantee is the constructive proof of Vizing’s theorem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] It shows how to color the edges of an undirected graph with at most $\Delta +1$ colors, where $\Delta$ is the maximum degree of any node.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Since every edge incident on a maximum-degree node must have a different color, the constructive proof of the theorem gives a polynomial-time algorithm that uses at most one additional color than the minimum needed.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] A notable example of an approximation algorithm that provides *both* is the classic approximation algorithm of Lenstra, Shmoys and Tardos for scheduling on unrelated parallel machines.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] The design and analysis of approximation algorithms crucially involves a mathematical proof certifying the quality of the returned solutions in the worst case.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] This distinguishes them from heuristics such as annealing or genetic algorithms, which find reasonably good solutions on some inputs, but provide no clear indication at the outset on when they may succeed or fail.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] There is widespread interest in theoretical computer science to better understand the limits to which we can approximate certain famous optimization problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] For example, one of the long-standing open questions in computer science is to determine whether there is an algorithm that outperforms the 2-approximation for the Steiner Forest problem by Agrawal et al.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] The desire to understand hard optimization problems from the perspective of approximability is motivated by the discovery of surprising mathematical connections and broadly applicable techniques to design algorithms for hard optimization problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] One well-known example of the former is the Goemans–Williamson algorithm for maximum cut, which solves a graph theoretic problem using a semidefinite program coming from the first level of the sum of squares hierarchy.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] A simple example of an approximation algorithm is one for the minimum vertex cover problem, where the goal is to choose the smallest set of vertices such that every edge in the input graph contains at least one chosen vertex.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] One way to find a vertex cover is to repeat the following process: find an uncovered edge, add both its endpoints to the cover, and remove all edges incident to either vertex from the graph.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] As any vertex cover of the input graph must use a distinct vertex to cover each edge that was considered in the process (since it forms a matching), the vertex cover produced, therefore, is at most twice as large as the optimal one.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In other words, this is a constant-factor approximation algorithm with an approximation factor of 2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Under the recent unique games conjecture, this factor is even the best possible one.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Others are impossible to approximate within any constant, or even polynomial, factor unless P = NP, as in the case of the maximum clique problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Therefore, an important benefit of studying approximation algorithms is a fine-grained classification of the difficulty of various NP-hard problems beyond the one afforded by the theory of NP-completeness.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In other words, although NP-complete problems may be equivalent (under polynomial-time reductions) to each other from the perspective of exact solutions, the corresponding optimization problems behave very differently from the perspective of approximate solutions.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] By now there are several established techniques to design approximation algorithms.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] This involves modeling the considered problem with an appropriate mathematical programming formulation (typically a convex programming) such as Linear programming, Semidefinite programming, etc, to obtain a relaxation of solutions for the problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Then further algorithmic techniques for these formulations are applied.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Embedding the problem in some metric and then solving the problem on the metric.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Random sampling and the use of randomness in general in conjunction with the methods above.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] While approximation algorithms always provide an a priori worst case guarantee (be it additive or multiplicative), in some cases they also provide an a posteriori guarantee that is often much better.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] This is often the case for algorithms that work by solving a convex relaxation of the optimization problem on the given input.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] For example, there is a different approximation algorithm for minimum vertex cover that solves a linear programming relaxation to find a vertex cover that is at most twice the value of the relaxation.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Since the value of the relaxation is never larger than the size of the optimal vertex cover, this yields another 2-approximation algorithm.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] While this is similar to the a priori guarantee of the previous approximation algorithm, the guarantee of the latter can be much better (indeed when the value of the LP relaxation is far from the size of the optimal vertex cover).
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Approximation algorithms as a research area is closely related to and informed by inapproximability theory where the non-existence of efficient algorithms with certain approximation ratios is proved (conditioned on widely believed hypotheses such as the P ≠ NP conjecture) by means of reductions.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In the case of the metric traveling salesman problem, the best known inapproximability result rules out algorithms with an approximation ratio less than 123/122 ≈ 1.008196 unless P = NP, Karpinski, Lampis, Schmied.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Coupled with the knowledge of the existence of Christofides' 1.5 approximation algorithm, this tells us that the threshold of approximability for metric traveling salesman (if it exists) is somewhere between 123/122 and 1.5.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] While inapproximability results have been proved since the 1970s, such results were obtained by ad hoc means and no systematic understanding was available at the time.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] It is only since the 1990 result of Feige, Goldwasser, Lovász, Safra and Szegedy on the inapproximability of Independent Set and the famous PCP theorem, that modern tools for proving inapproximability results were uncovered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] The PCP theorem, for example, shows that Johnson's 1974 approximation algorithms for Max SAT, set cover, independent set and coloring all achieve the optimal approximation ratio, assuming P ≠ NP.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Not all approximation algorithms are suitable for direct practical applications.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Implementation and running time issues aside, the guarantees provided by approximation algorithms may themselves not be strong enough to justify their consideration in practice.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Despite their inability to be used "out of the box" in practical applications, the ideas and insights behind the design of such algorithms can often be incorporated in other ways in practical algorithms.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In this way, the study of even very expensive algorithms is not a completely theoretical pursuit as they can yield valuable insights.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In other cases, even if the initial results are of purely theoretical interest, over time, with an improved understanding, the algorithms may be refined to become more practical.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] One such example is the initial PTAS for Euclidean TSP by Sanjeev Arora (and independently by Joseph Mitchell) which had a prohibitive running time of $n^{O(1/\epsilon )}$ for a $1+\epsilon$ approximation.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Yet, within a year these ideas were incorporated into a near-linear time $O(n\log n)$ algorithm for any constant $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Given a feasible solution $s\in S(i)$ , with $s\neq s^{*}$ , we would want a guarantee of the quality of the solution, which is a performance to be guaranteed (approximation factor).
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] The approximation can be proven *tight* (*tight approximation*) by demonstrating that there exist instances where the algorithm performs at the approximation limit, indicating the tightness of the bound.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In this case, it's enough to construct an input instance designed to force the algorithm into a worst-case scenario.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] For some approximation algorithms it is possible to prove certain properties about the approximation of the optimum result.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] The factor *ρ* is called the *relative performance guarantee*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] where *f*(*y*) is the value/cost of the solution *y* for the instance *x*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Clearly, the performance guarantee is greater than or equal to 1 and equal to 1 if and only if *y* is an optimal solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] If an algorithm *A* guarantees to return solutions with a performance guarantee of at most *r*(*n*), then *A* is said to be an *r*(*n*)-approximation algorithm and has an *approximation ratio* of *r*(*n*).
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Likewise, a problem with an *r*(*n*)-approximation algorithm is said to be r*(*n*)*-*approximable* or have an approximation ratio of *r*(*n*).
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] For minimization problems, the two different guarantees provide the same result and that for maximization problems, a relative performance guarantee of ρ is equivalent to a performance guarantee of $r=\rho ^{-1}$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In the literature, both definitions are common but it is clear which definition is used since, for maximization problems, as ρ ≤ 1 while r ≥ 1.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] That is to say that $\mathrm {P} _{A}$ is the largest bound on the approximation ratio, *r*, that one sees over all possible instances of the problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] That is to say that it is the same as the *absolute performance ratio*, with a lower bound *n* on the size of problem instances.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] These two types of ratios are used because there exist algorithms where the difference between these two is significant.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In the literature, an approximation ratio for a maximization (minimization) problem of *c* - ϵ (min: *c* + ϵ) means that the algorithm has an approximation ratio of *c* ∓ ϵ for arbitrary ϵ > 0 but that the ratio has not (or cannot) be shown for ϵ = 0.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] An example of this is the optimal inapproximability — inexistence of approximation — ratio of 7 / 8 + ϵ for satisfiable MAX-3SAT instances due to Johan Håstad.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] As mentioned previously, when *c* = 1, the problem is said to have a polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] An ϵ-term may appear when an approximation algorithm introduces a multiplicative error and a constant error while the minimum optimum of instances of size *n* goes to infinity as *n* does.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] In this case, the approximation ratio is *c* ∓ *k* / OPT = *c* ∓ o(1) for some constants *c* and *k*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] Given arbitrary ϵ > 0, one can choose a large enough *N* such that the term *k* / OPT < ϵ for every *n ≥ N*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/approximation-algorithm] For every fixed ϵ, instances of size *n < N* can be solved by brute force, thereby showing an approximation ratio — existence of approximation algorithms with a guarantee — of *c* ∓ ϵ for every ϵ > 0.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] In computational complexity theory, the class **APX** (an abbreviation of "approximable") is the set of **NP** optimization problems that allow polynomial-time approximation algorithms with approximation ratio bounded by a constant (or **constant-factor approximation algorithms** for short).
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] In simple terms, problems in this class have efficient algorithms that can find an answer within some fixed multiplicative factor of the optimal answer.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] An approximation algorithm is called an $f(n)$ -approximation algorithm for input size n if it can be proven that the solution that the algorithm finds is at most a multiplicative factor of $f(n)$ times worse than the optimal solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Here, $f(n)$ is called the *approximation ratio*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] **Problems in APX** are those with algorithms for which the approximation ratio $f(n)$ is a constant c .
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] The approximation ratio is conventionally stated greater than 1.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] In the case of minimization problems, $f(n)$ is the found solution's score divided by the optimum solution's score, while for maximization problems the reverse is the case.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] For maximization problems, where an inferior solution has a smaller score, $f(n)$ is sometimes stated as less than 1; in such cases, the reciprocal of $f(n)$ is the ratio of the score of the found solution to the score of the optimum solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] A problem is said to have a polynomial-time approximation scheme (**PTAS**) if for *every* multiplicative factor of the optimum worse than 1 there is a polynomial-time algorithm to solve the problem to within that factor.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Unless P = NP there exist problems that are in APX but without a PTAS, so the class of problems with a PTAS is strictly contained in APX.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] One example of a problem with a PTAS is the knapsack problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] A problem is said to be **APX-hard** if there is a PTAS reduction from every problem in APX to that problem, and to be **APX-complete** if the problem is APX-hard and also in APX.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] As a consequence of P ≠ NP ⇒ PTAS ≠ APX, if P ≠ NP is assumed, no APX-hard problem has a PTAS.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] In practice, reducing one problem to another to demonstrate APX-completeness is often done using other reduction schemes, such as L-reductions, which imply PTAS reductions.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] One of the simplest APX-complete problems is MAX-3SAT, a variation of the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] In this problem, we have a Boolean formula in conjunctive normal form where each variable appears at most 3 times, and we wish to know the maximum number of clauses that can be simultaneously satisfied by a single assignment of true/false values to the variables.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] PTAS (*polynomial time approximation scheme*) consists of problems that can be approximated to within any constant factor besides 1 in time that is polynomial to the input size, but the polynomial depends on such factor.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Unless P = NP, there exist problems in APX that are neither in PTAS nor APX-complete.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Such problems can be thought of as having a hardness between PTAS problems and APX-complete problems, and may be called **APX-intermediate**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] The bin packing problem is thought to be APX-intermediate.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Despite not having a known PTAS, the bin packing problem has several "asymptotic PTAS" algorithms, which behave like a PTAS when the optimum solution is large, so intuitively it may be easier than problems that are APX-hard.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] One other example of a potentially APX-intermediate problem is min edge coloring.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] One can also define a family of complexity classes $f(n)$ -APX, where $f(n)$ -APX contains problems with a polynomial time approximation algorithm with a $O(f(n))$ approximation ratio.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] One can analogously define $f(n)$ -APX-complete classes; some such classes contain well-known optimization problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Log-APX-completeness and poly-APX-completeness are defined in terms of AP-reductions rather than PTAS-reductions; this is because PTAS-reductions are not strong enough to preserve membership in Log-APX and Poly-APX, even though they suffice for APX.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Log-APX-complete, consisting of the hardest problems that can be approximated efficiently to within a factor logarithmic in the input size, includes min dominating set when degree is unbounded.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] Poly-APX-complete, consisting of the hardest problems that can be approximated efficiently to within a factor polynomial in the input size, includes max independent set in the general case.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] There also exist problems that are exp-APX-complete, where the approximation ratio is exponential in the input size.
[src:approximation-algorithms/apx] This may occur when the approximation is dependent on the value of numbers within the problem instance; these numbers may be expressed in space logarithmic in their value, hence the exponential factor.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The **Christofides algorithm** or **Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm** is an algorithm for finding approximate solutions to the travelling salesman problem, on instances where the distances form a metric space (they are symmetric and obey the triangle inequality).
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] It is an approximation algorithm that guarantees that its solutions will be within a factor of 3/2 of the optimal solution length, and is named after Nicos Christofides and Anatoliy Serdyukov (Russian: Анатолий Иванович Сердюков).
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Christofides published the algorithm in 1976; Serdyukov discovered it independently in 1976 but published it in 1978.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Let *G* = (*V*,*w*) be an instance of the travelling salesman problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] That is, G is a complete graph on the set V of vertices, and the function w assigns a nonnegative real weight to every edge of G.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] According to the triangle inequality, for every three vertices u, v, and x, it should be the case that *w*(*uv*) + *w*(*vx*) ≥ *w*(*ux*).
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Then the algorithm can be described in pseudocode as follows.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Let O be the set of vertices with odd degree in T.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] By the handshaking lemma, O has an even number of vertices.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Find a minimum-weight perfect matching M in the subgraph induced in G by O.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Combine the edges of M and T to form a connected multigraph H in which each vertex has even degree.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Make the circuit found in previous step into a Hamiltonian circuit by skipping repeated vertices (*shortcutting*).
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Steps 5 and 6 do not necessarily yield only a single result; as such, the heuristic can give several different paths.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The worst-case complexity of the algorithm is dominated by the perfect matching step, which has $O(n^{3})$ complexity.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Serdyukov's paper claimed $O(n^{3}\log n)$ complexity, because the author was only aware of a less efficient perfect matching algorithm.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The cost of the solution produced by the algorithm is within 3/2 of the optimum.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] To prove this, let C be the optimal traveling salesman tour.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Removing an edge from C produces a spanning tree, which must have weight at least that of the minimum spanning tree, implying that *w*(*T*) ≤ *w*(*C*) - lower bound to the cost of the optimal solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The algorithm addresses the problem that T is not a tour by identifying all the odd degree vertices in T; since the sum of degrees in any graph is even (by the handshaking lemma), there is an even number of such vertices.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The algorithm finds a minimum-weight perfect matching M among the odd-degree ones.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Next, number the vertices of O in cyclic order around C, and partition C into two sets of paths: the ones in which the first path vertex in cyclic order has an odd number and the ones in which the first path vertex has an even number.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Each set of paths corresponds to a perfect matching of O that matches the two endpoints of each path, and the weight of this matching is at most equal to the weight of the paths.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] In fact, each path endpoint will be connected to another endpoint, which also has an odd number of visits due to the nature of the tour.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Since these two sets of paths partition the edges of C, one of the two sets has at most half of the weight of C, and thanks to the triangle inequality its corresponding matching has weight that is also at most half the weight of C.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The minimum-weight perfect matching can have no larger weight, so *w*(*M*) ≤ *w*(*C*)/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Adding the weights of T and M gives the weight of the Euler tour, at most 3*w*(*C*)/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Thanks to the triangle inequality, even though the Euler tour might revisit vertices, shortcutting does not increase the weight, so the weight of the output is also at most 3*w*(*C*)/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] There exist inputs to the travelling salesman problem that cause the Christofides algorithm to find a solution whose approximation ratio is arbitrarily close to 3/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] One such class of inputs are formed by a path of n vertices, with the path edges having weight 1, together with a set of edges connecting vertices two steps apart in the path with weight 1 + *ε* for a number *ε* chosen close to zero but positive.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] All remaining edges of the complete graph have distances given by the shortest paths in this subgraph.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Then the minimum spanning tree will be given by the path, of length *n* − 1, and the only two odd vertices will be the path endpoints, whose perfect matching consists of a single edge with weight approximately *n*/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The union of the tree and the matching is a cycle, with no possible shortcuts, and with weight approximately 3*n*/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] However, the optimal solution uses the edges of weight 1 + *ε* together with two weight-1 edges incident to the endpoints of the path, and has total weight (1 + *ε*)(*n* − 2) + 2, close to n for small values of *ε*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Hence we obtain an approximation ratio of 3/2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] This algorithm is no longer the best polynomial time approximation algorithm for the TSP on general metric spaces.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Karlin, Klein, and Gharan introduced a randomized approximation algorithm with approximation ratio 1.5 − 10−36.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] It follows similar principles to Christofides' algorithm, but uses a randomly chosen tree from a carefully chosen random distribution in place of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] The paper received a best paper award at the 2021 Symposium on Theory of Computing.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] For each constant c this time bound is in polynomial time, so this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their simultaneous discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] Methods based on the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm can also be used to approximate the stacker crane problem, a generalization of the TSP in which the input consists of ordered pairs of points from a metric space that must be traversed consecutively and in order.
[src:approximation-algorithms/christofides-algorithm] For this problem, it achieves an approximation ratio of 9/5.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] In computer science, **hardness of approximation** is a field that studies the algorithmic complexity of finding near-optimal solutions to optimization problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] Hardness of approximation complements the study of approximation algorithms by proving, for certain problems, a limit on the factors with which their solution can be efficiently approximated.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] Typically such limits show a factor of approximation beyond which a problem becomes NP-hard, implying that finding a polynomial time approximation for the problem is impossible unless NP=P.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] Some hardness of approximation results, however, are based on other hypotheses, a notable one among which is the unique games conjecture.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] Since the early 1970s it was known that many optimization problems could not be solved in polynomial time unless P = NP, but in many of these problems the optimal solution could be efficiently approximated to a certain degree.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] Gonzalez and Sartaj Sahni began the study of hardness of approximation, by showing that certain optimization problems were NP-hard even to approximate to within a given approximation ratio.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] That is, for these problems, there is a threshold such that any polynomial-time approximation with approximation ratio beyond this threshold could be used to solve NP-complete problems in polynomial time.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] In the early 1990s, with the development of PCP theory, it became clear that many more approximation problems were hard to approximate, and that (unless P = NP) many known approximation algorithms achieved the best possible approximation ratio.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] Hardness of approximation theory deals with studying the approximation threshold of such problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/hardness-of-approximation] For an example of an NP-hard optimization problem that is hard to approximate, see set cover and vertex cover.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] In computer science (particularly algorithmics), a **polynomial-time approximation scheme** (**PTAS**) is a type of approximation algorithm for optimization problems (most often, NP-hard optimization problems).
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] A PTAS is an algorithm which takes an instance of an optimization problem and a parameter ε > 0 and produces a solution that is within a factor 1 + ε of being optimal (or 1 – ε for maximization problems).
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] For example, for the Euclidean traveling salesman problem, a PTAS would produce a tour with length at most (1 + ε)*L*, with L being the length of the shortest tour.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] The running time of a PTAS is required to be polynomial in the problem size for every fixed ε, but can be different for different ε.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Thus an algorithm running in time *O*(*n*1/ε) or even *O*(*n*exp(1/ε)) counts as a PTAS.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] A practical problem with PTAS algorithms is that the exponent of the polynomial could increase dramatically as ε shrinks, for example if the runtime is *O*(*n*(1/ε)!).
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] One way of addressing this is to define the **efficient polynomial-time approximation scheme** or **EPTAS**, in which the running time is required to be *O*(*n**c*) for a constant c independent of ε.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] This ensures that an increase in problem size has the same relative effect on runtime regardless of what ε is being used; however, the constant under the big-O can still depend on ε arbitrarily.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] In other words, an EPTAS runs in FPT time where the parameter is ε.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Even more restrictive, and useful in practice, is the **fully polynomial-time approximation scheme** or **FPTAS**, which requires the algorithm to be polynomial in both the problem size n and 1/ε.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Unless P = NP, it holds that FPTAS ⊊ PTAS ⊊ APX.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Consequently, under this assumption, APX-hard problems do not have PTASs.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Another deterministic variant of the PTAS is the **quasi-polynomial-time approximation scheme** or **QPTAS**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] A QPTAS has time complexity *n*polylog(*n*) for each fixed ε > 0.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Furthermore, a PTAS can run in FPT time for some parameterization of the problem, which leads to a parameterized approximation scheme.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Some problems which do not have a PTAS may admit a randomized algorithm with similar properties, a **polynomial-time randomized approximation scheme** or **PRAS**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] A PRAS is an algorithm which takes an instance of an optimization or counting problem and a parameter ε > 0 and, in polynomial time, produces a solution that has a *high probability* of being within a factor ε of optimal.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Conventionally, "high probability" means probability greater than 3/4, though as with most probabilistic complexity classes the definition is robust to variations in this exact value (the bare minimum requirement is generally greater than 1/2).
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] The term PTAS may also be used to refer to the class of optimization problems that have a PTAS.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] PTAS is a subset of APX, and unless P = NP, it is a strict subset.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] Membership in PTAS can be shown using a PTAS reduction, L-reduction, or P-reduction, all of which preserve PTAS membership, and these may also be used to demonstrate PTAS-completeness.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] On the other hand, showing non-membership in PTAS (namely, the nonexistence of a PTAS), may be done by showing that the problem is APX-hard, after which the existence of a PTAS would show P = NP.
[src:approximation-algorithms/polynomial-time-approximation-scheme] APX-hardness is commonly shown via PTAS reduction or AP-reduction.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The **set cover problem** is a classical question in combinatorics, computer science, operations research, and complexity theory.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] In this example, m is equal to 4, as there are four subsets that comprise this collection.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] However, we can cover all elements with only two sets: { {1, 2, 3}, {4, 5} }‍, see picture, but not with only one set.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Therefore, the solution to the set cover problem for this U and S has size 2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] More formally, given a universe ${\mathcal {U}}$ and a family ${\mathcal {S}}$ of subsets of ${\mathcal {U}}$ , a **set cover** is a subfamily ${\mathcal {C}}\subseteq {\mathcal {S}}$ of sets whose union is ${\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The decision version of set covering is NP-complete.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] It is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems shown to be NP-complete in 1972.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The optimization/search version of set cover is NP-hard.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] It is a problem "whose study has led to the development of fundamental techniques for the entire field" of approximation algorithms.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] In the **weighted set cover** problem, each set is assigned a positive weight (representing its cost), and the goal is to find a set cover with a smallest weight.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The usual (unweighted) set cover corresponds to all sets having a weight of 1.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] In the **fractional set cover** problem, it is allowed to select fractions of sets, rather than entire sets.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] A fractional set cover is an assignment of a fraction (a number in [0,1]) to each set in ${\mathcal {S}}$ , such that for each element *x* in the universe, the sum of fractions of sets that contain *x* is at least 1.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The goal is to find a fractional set cover in which the sum of fractions is as small as possible.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Note that a (usual) set cover is equivalent to a fractional set cover in which all fractions are either 0 or 1; therefore, the size of the smallest fractional cover is at most the size of the smallest cover, but may be smaller.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] But there is a fractional set cover of size 1.5, in which a 0.5 fraction of each set is taken.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] In the **capacitated set cover** problem, each set $s\in {\mathcal {S}}$ is associated with a capacity $c_{S}$ which denotes the number of elements it can supply coverage.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The goal is to determine the optimal way to select sets such that each element receives the coverage it requires.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The **set cover problem** can be formulated as the following integer linear program (ILP).
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] For a more compact representation of the covering constraint, one can define an incidence matrix *A*, where each row corresponds to an element and each column corresponds to a set, and *$A_{e,s}=1$* if element e is in set s, and *$A_{e,s}=0$* otherwise.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Then, the covering constraint can be written as $Ax\geqslant 1$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] This linear program belongs to the more general class of LPs for covering problems, as all the coefficients in the objective function and both sides of the constraints are non-negative.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The integrality gap of the ILP is at most $\scriptstyle \log n$ (where $\scriptstyle n$ is the size of the universe).
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] It has been shown that its relaxation indeed gives a factor- $\scriptstyle \log n$ approximation algorithm for the minimum set cover problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] See setcover for a detailed explanation.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The set cover problem is equivalent to the hitting set problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] A subset H of U is called a **hitting set** when $H\cap S_{j}\neq \emptyset$ for all $1\leq j\leq m$ (i.e., H intersects or “hits” all subsets in S ).
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The **hitting set problem** is to find a minimum hitting set H for a given U and S .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] To show that the problems are equivalent, for a universe U of size n and collection of sets S of size m , construct $U'=\{1,2,\ldots ,m\}$ and $S'_{i}=\{j\mid i\in S_{j}\}$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Then a set cover C of S is equivalent to a hitting set $H'$ of $U'$ where $S_{j}\in C\iff j\in H'$ , and vice versa.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Then a set cover is a subset C of right vertices such that each left vertex is adjacent to at least one member of C , while a hitting set is a subset H of left vertices such that each right vertex is adjacent to at least one member of H .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] These definitions are exactly the same except that *left* and *right* are swapped.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] But there is nothing special about the sides in the bipartite graph; we could have put the elements of U on the right side, and the elements of S on the left side, creating a graph that is a mirror image of the one described above.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] This shows that set covers in the original graph are equivalent to hitting sets in the mirrored graph, and vice versa.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] In the field of computational geometry, a hitting set for a collection of geometrical objects is also called a **stabbing set** or **piercing set**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] There is a greedy algorithm for polynomial time approximation of set covering that chooses sets according to one rule: at each stage, choose the set that contains the largest number of uncovered elements.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] This method can be implemented in time linear in the sum of sizes of the input sets, using a bucket queue to prioritize the sets.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] It achieves an approximation ratio of $H(s)$ , where s is the size of the set to be covered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] This greedy algorithm actually achieves an approximation ratio of $H(s^{\prime })$ where $s^{\prime }$ is the maximum cardinality set of S .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] For $\delta -$ dense instances, however, there exists a $c\ln {m}$ -approximation algorithm for every $c>0$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] There is a standard example on which the greedy algorithm achieves an approximation ratio of $\log _{2}(n)/2$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The universe consists of $n=2^{(k+1)}-2$ elements.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The set system consists of k pairwise disjoint sets $S_{1},\ldots ,S_{k}$ with sizes $2,4,8,\ldots ,2^{k}$ respectively, as well as two additional disjoint sets $T_{0},T_{1}$ , each of which contains half of the elements from each $S_{i}$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] On this input, the greedy algorithm takes the sets $S_{k},\ldots ,S_{1}$ , in that order, while the optimal solution consists only of $T_{0}$ and $T_{1}$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] An example of such an input for $k=3$ is pictured on the right.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Inapproximability results show that the greedy algorithm is essentially the best-possible polynomial time approximation algorithm for set cover up to lower order terms (see Inapproximability results below), under plausible complexity assumptions.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] A tighter analysis for the greedy algorithm shows that the approximation ratio is exactly $\ln {n}-\ln {\ln {n}}+\Theta (1)$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] If each element occurs in at most *f* sets, then a solution can be found in polynomial time that approximates the optimum to within a factor of *f* using LP relaxation.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] If the constraint $x_{S}\in \{0,1\}$ is replaced by $x_{S}\geq 0$ for all *S* in ${\mathcal {S}}$ in the integer linear program shown above, then it becomes a (non-integer) linear program *L*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Pick all sets *S* for which the corresponding variable *x**S* has value at least 1/*f* in the solution *O*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] When n refers to the size of the universe, Lund & Yannakakis (1994) showed that set covering cannot be approximated in polynomial time to within a factor of ${\tfrac {1}{2}}\log _{2}{n}\approx 0.72\ln {n}$ , unless **NP** has quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Feige (1998) improved this lower bound to ${\bigl (}1-o(1){\bigr )}\cdot \ln {n}$ under the same assumptions, which essentially matches the approximation ratio achieved by the greedy algorithm.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Raz & Safra (1997) established a lower bound of $c\cdot \ln {n}$ , where c is a certain constant, under the weaker assumption that **P** $\not =$ **NP**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] A similar result with a higher value of c was recently proved by Alon, Moshkovitz & Safra (2006).
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Dinur & Steurer (2013) showed optimal inapproximability by proving that it cannot be approximated to ${\bigl (}1-o(1){\bigr )}\cdot \ln {n}$ unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] (2003) proved it is NP-hard to approximate set cover to better than $f-1-\epsilon$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] If the Unique games conjecture is true, this can be improved to $f-\epsilon$ as proven by Khot & Regev (2008).
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Trevisan (2001) proves that set cover instances with sets of size at most $\Delta$ cannot be approximated to a factor better than $\ln \Delta -O(\ln \ln \Delta )$ unless **P** = **NP**, thus making the approximation of $\ln \Delta +1$ of the greedy algorithm essentially tight in this case.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The **greedy algorithm** for the weighted set cover problem directly generalizes the unweighted version.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Given a universe ${\mathcal {U}}$ and a family ${\mathcal {S}}$ of subsets of ${\mathcal {U}}$ , where each set $S\in {\mathcal {S}}$ is assigned a non-negative weight (cost), the algorithm maintains the subset of elements that are not yet covered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Initially, all elements of ${\mathcal {U}}$ are uncovered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] At each iteration, the algorithm selects a set $S\in {\mathcal {S}}$ that minimizes the ratio between its weight and the number of currently uncovered elements it contains.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The selected set is added to the solution, and all elements contained in it are marked as covered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] This process is repeated until all elements of ${\mathcal {U}}$ are covered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The greedy algorithm is known to produce a solution whose total weight is at most a factor of $H(n)$ times the optimal solution, where $H(n)$ denotes the n -th harmonic number and $n=|{\mathcal {U}}|$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] For low frequency systems, where every element is contained in at most f sets, the **deterministic LP rounding** algorithm gets an f -approximation.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] It starts with the optimal solution to the linear programming relaxation of the problem stated above.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Sets whose fractional value exceeds $1/f$ are selected to form an integer solution.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The **primal-dual algorithm** for the set cover problem is an iterative method that constructs feasible solutions to both the primal and dual linear programs simultaneously.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] Starting with all dual variables set to zero, the algorithm repeatedly increases the dual variables corresponding to uncovered elements uniformly, until some set’s dual constraint becomes tight (i.e., the sum of the dual variables for elements in the set equals its cost).
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] This tight set is then added to the primal solution, covering the corresponding elements.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The process continues until all elements are covered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/set-cover-problem] The algorithm guarantees an approximation ratio of f , where f is the maximum number of sets that any element belongs to.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] In graph theory, a **vertex cover** (sometimes **node cover**) of a graph is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of every edge of the graph.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] In computer science, the problem of finding a **minimum vertex cover** is a classical optimization problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] It is NP-hard, so it cannot be solved by a polynomial-time algorithm if P ≠ NP.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Moreover, it is hard to approximate – it cannot be approximated up to a factor smaller than 2 if the unique games conjecture is true.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] On the other hand, it has several simple 2-factor approximations.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] It is a typical example of an NP-hard optimization problem that has an approximation algorithm.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Its decision version, the **vertex cover problem**, was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems and is therefore a classical NP-complete problem in computational complexity theory.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Furthermore, the vertex cover problem is fixed-parameter tractable and a central problem in parameterized complexity theory.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The minimum vertex cover problem can be formulated as a half-integral, linear program whose dual linear program is the maximum matching problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Vertex cover problems have been generalized to hypergraphs, see *Vertex cover in hypergraphs*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Formally, a vertex cover $V'$ of an undirected graph $G=(V,E)$ is a subset of V such that $(uv\in E)\Rightarrow (u\in V'\lor v\in V')$ , that is to say it is a set of vertices $V'$ where every edge has at least one endpoint in the vertex cover $V'$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Such a set is said to *cover* the edges of G .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The upper figure shows two examples of vertex covers, with some vertex cover $V'$ marked in red.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] A *minimum vertex cover* is a vertex cover of smallest possible size.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The vertex cover number $\tau$ is the size of a minimum vertex cover, i.e. $\tau =|V'|$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The lower figure shows examples of minimum vertex covers in the previous graphs.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The **minimum vertex cover problem** is the optimization problem of finding a smallest vertex cover in a given graph.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] They are equivalent under polynomial-time reduction by using binary search.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The vertex cover problem is an NP-complete problem: it was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] It is often used in computational complexity theory as a starting point for NP-hardness proofs.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Assume that every vertex has an associated cost of $c(v)\geq 0$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The (weighted) minimum vertex cover problem can be formulated as the following integer linear program (ILP).
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] This ILP belongs to the more general class of ILPs for covering problems.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The integrality gap of this ILP is 2 , so its relaxation (allowing each variable to be in the interval from 0 to 1, rather than requiring the variables to be only 0 or 1) gives a factor- 2 approximation algorithm for the minimum vertex cover problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Furthermore, the linear programming relaxation of that ILP is *half-integral*, that is, there exists an optimal solution for which each entry $x_{v}$ is either 0, 1/2, or 1.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] A 2-approximate vertex cover can be obtained from this fractional solution by selecting the subset of vertices whose variables are nonzero.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The decision variant of the vertex cover problem is NP-complete, which means it is unlikely that there is an efficient algorithm to solve it exactly for arbitrary graphs.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] NP-completeness can be proven by reduction from 3-satisfiability or, as Karp did, by reduction from the clique problem.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Vertex cover remains NP-complete even in cubic graphs and even in planar graphs of degree at most 3.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] For bipartite graphs, the equivalence between vertex cover and maximum matching described by Kőnig's theorem allows the bipartite vertex cover problem to be solved in polynomial time.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] For tree graphs, an algorithm finds a minimal vertex cover in polynomial time by finding the first leaf in the tree and adding its parent to the minimal vertex cover, then deleting the leaf and parent and all associated edges and continuing repeatedly until no edges remain in the tree.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] An exhaustive search algorithm can solve the problem in time 2*k**n**O*(1), where *k* is the size of the vertex cover.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Vertex cover is therefore fixed-parameter tractable, and if we are only interested in small *k*, we can solve the problem in polynomial time.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] One algorithmic technique that works here is called *bounded search tree algorithm*, and its idea is to repeatedly choose some vertex and recursively branch, with two cases at each step: place either the current vertex or all its neighbours into the vertex cover.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The algorithm for solving vertex cover that achieves the best asymptotic dependence on the parameter runs in time $O(1.2738^{k}+(k\cdot n))$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The klam value of this time bound (an estimate for the largest parameter value that could be solved in a reasonable amount of time) is approximately 190.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] That is, unless additional algorithmic improvements can be found, this algorithm is suitable only for instances whose vertex cover number is 190 or less.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Under reasonable complexity-theoretic assumptions, namely the exponential time hypothesis, the running time cannot be improved to 2*o*(*k*), even when n is $O(k)$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] However, for planar graphs, and more generally, for graphs excluding some fixed graph as a minor, a vertex cover of size *k* can be found in time *$2^{O({\sqrt {k}})}n^{O(1)}$*, i.e., the problem is subexponential fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] This algorithm is again optimal, in the sense that, under the exponential time hypothesis, no algorithm can solve vertex cover on planar graphs in time *$2^{o({\sqrt {k}})}n^{O(1)}$*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] One can find a factor-2 approximation by repeatedly taking *both* endpoints of an edge into the vertex cover, then removing them from the graph.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Put otherwise, we find a maximal matching *M* with a greedy algorithm and construct a vertex cover *C* that consists of all endpoints of the edges in *M*.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] In the following figure, a maximal matching *M* is marked with red, and the vertex cover *C* is marked with blue.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The set *C* constructed this way is a vertex cover: suppose that an edge *e* is not covered by *C*; then *M* ∪ {*e*} is a matching and *e* ∉ *M*, which is a contradiction with the assumption that *M* is maximal.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Furthermore, if *e* = {*u*, *v*} ∈ *M*, then any vertex cover – including an optimal vertex cover – must contain *u* or *v* (or both); otherwise the edge *e* is not covered.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] That is, an optimal cover contains at least *one* endpoint of each edge in *M*; in total, the set *C* is at most 2 times as large as the optimal vertex cover.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] This simple algorithm was discovered independently by Fanica Gavril and Mihalis Yannakakis.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] More involved techniques show that there are approximation algorithms with a slightly better approximation factor.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] For example, an approximation algorithm with an approximation factor of ${\textstyle 2-\Theta \left(1/{\sqrt {\log |V|}}\right)}$ is known.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The problem can be approximated with an approximation factor $2/(1+\delta )$ in $\delta$ - dense graphs.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] No better constant-factor approximation algorithm than the above one is known.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] The minimum vertex cover problem is APX-complete, that is, it cannot be approximated arbitrarily well unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Using techniques from the PCP theorem, Dinur and Safra proved in 2005 that minimum vertex cover cannot be approximated within a factor of 1.3606 for any sufficiently large vertex degree unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Later, the factor was improved to ${\sqrt {2}}-\epsilon$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Moreover, if the unique games conjecture is true then minimum vertex cover cannot be approximated within any constant factor better than 2.
[src:approximation-algorithms/vertex-cover] Although finding the minimum-size vertex cover is equivalent to finding the maximum-size independent set, as described above, the two problems are not equivalent in an approximation-preserving way: The Independent Set problem has *no* constant-factor approximation unless **P** = **NP**.
